</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64960761">The tariffs are going to spike inflation. <br> <br>

To fight that inflation the federal reserve will hike interest rates up, because that's what they do. <br> <br>

Now, let's talk about <i>how</i> and <i>why</i> high interest rates "fight" inflation, because it's not something anyone really talks about. <br>br&gt;

See, it's suddenly expensive to borrow money. Most companies expand using borrowed money. So they stop expanding. Heck, they start *contracting*. <br> <br>

That means layoffs. Mass layoffs. If you're in Tech you're already seeing it, which is why you're "stuck". <br> <br>

The idea is we all get fired, blow through our savings, and massively pull back on spending. That forces companies to cut prices when demand tanks. <br> <br>

It's balancing the books on our backs. <br> <br>

This only works if there's competition, but we've had decades of unchecked market consolidation. So there's no real reason for companies to cut prices except the threat of anti-trust law enforcement and regulation. <br> <br>

And those are right out the window now. <br> <br>

So buckle up folks, <a href="https://www.marketwatch.com/story/kaboom-elon-musk-predicts-hardship-economic-turmoil-and-a-stock-market-crash-if-trump-wins-20483008" title="marketwatch.com">we voted for this. </a> [marketwatch.com]</div>
	</div>

